{
  "text": "Sometimes we are more interested in d \u03b1 (\u03b1) than d (\u03b1) . For example, the classical JL Lemma for l 2 is presented in terms of the squared l 2 distance. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] approximated the Hamming norm using the l \u03b1 norm raised to \u03b1th power, with very small \u03b1. Obviously we could raise the estimator (e.g.,d (\u03b1),gm ) to the \u03b1th power, as treated in [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . We are concerned about the tail bounds, because a (1 \u00b1 \u01eb) \u03b1 factor becomes a 1 \u00b1 \u01eb 2 factor when \u03b1 = \u01eb.",
